{"title_page": "African Clean Energy", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=December 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = African Clean Energy\n| logo = [[File:ACE Logo Small.png|ACE Logo Small.png]]\n| location = [[Amsterdam]]\n}}\n'''African Clean Energy''' is a [[social enterprise]] that produces and distributes solar-biomass hybrid energy systems in [[developing countries]]. The company was founded in Lesotho, where it manufactures the ACE One Energy System. The company's headquarters are in Amsterdam, The Netherlands.<ref name=\"DutchSocialEntrepreneur\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/devinthorpe/2015/09/02/dutch-social-entrepreneur-works-to-save-lives-in-africa-with-high-tech-stove/2/#13780e96f914 |title=Dutch Social Entrepreneur Works To Save Lives In Africa With High Tech Stove |last=Thorpe |first=Devin |date=2 September 2015 |website=Forbes |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\">{{cite book |last=Haber |first=Jason |date=16 May 2016 |title=The Business of Good, Social Entrepreneurship and the New Bottom Line |url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=A5IfDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&pg=GBS.PT30.w.5.0.105 |publisher=Entrepreneur Press |pages=16\u201317 |isbn=9781613083369}}</ref><ref name=\"AMSMagazine2017\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Update:Social Enterprises |url=https://s3-eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/africancleanenergy-storage-temp/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Amsteram-Magazine-Talent-Issue.png |magazine=AMS Business Magazine |location=Amsterdam |date=2017 |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nAfrican Clean Energy (ACE) is a family-owned business, founded in 2011 by Ruben Walker and his father, Stephen Walker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. Ruben Walker studied environmental engineering in Australia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. Prior to founding ACE, Ruben owned a bamboo flooring company, as a sustainable alternative to wood<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. The ACE One was developed in 2014 with support from crowdfunding and the [[Global Alliance for Clean Cookstoves]].<ref name=\"YoungJudithWalker\">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/26/young-entrepreneur-judith-walker-ace_n_5875412.html |title=Young Entrepreneur Of The Week: 24-Year-Old Judith Walker |last=Bennett |first=Asa |date=26 September 2014 |website=Huffpost |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\nAs of 2017, the company is active in Lesotho, Cambodia and Uganda.<ref name=\"AMSMagazine2017\" />Stephen Walker, an expert in manufacturing, helped set up ACE's factories in Lesotho and Cambodia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. The company expects to open a third factory in Uganda in 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>.\n\n==The Biomass Cooking Sector==\n\nMore than 3 billion people cook using solid [[biomass fuels]] like wood, crop waste, coal and animal dung. There are also 1.2 billion people without access to electricity, who currently rely on dangerous fuels like kerosene for lighting.<ref name=\"HouseholdAir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs292/en/|title=Household air pollution and health|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=February 2016|website=World Health Organization|access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe World Health Organization estimates that 4.3 million people die prematurely every year from illnesses attributable to household air pollution from burning solid fuels. These include lung cancer, stroke, heart disease, pulmonary disease and childhood pneumonia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. Exposure to indoor smoke is particularly high amongst women and girls, who are typically responsible for cooking. The responsibility of sourcing fuel for cooking and heating also predominantly falls on women, who spend hours each day collecting firewood for their homes, cutting short their potential to study or do other things<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. \n\nThe ACE One Energy System was designed to address these issues, while still being compatible with widely available biomass fuels, such as sticks, animal waste and agricultural waste<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. It is capable of burning any type of solid biomass smokelessly, and provides electricity for households that do not have access to the grid.<ref name=\"UltraCleanSafe\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Ultra Clean and Super Safe |url=https://issuu.com/imarketinsights/docs/imarket_insights_issue_02_2017 |magazine=IMarket Insights |publisher=Sunil Bhat |pages=30, 32 |date= 2017 |access-date= 29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==The Product==\n\n===Functionality===\n\nThe ACE One has an integrated lithium-ion ferrophosphate battery which powers a small fan. The fan draws oxygen into the burning chamber of the device, intensifying the fire inside. This causes the biomass to gasify, ensuring complete combustion and creating a smokeless flame. The battery will power the fan for 20 hours, and can be charged using the included 5W solar panel.<ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" /><ref name=\"GearWired\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Gear |url=http://www.africancleanenergy.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/WIRED-MAG.jpg |magazine=Wired Magazine |location= |publisher=Rupert Turnbull |page=69 |date= 2015 |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> The latest ACE One includes a microprocessor and is sold with a second-use Samsung smartphone, giving the device \"smart\" capabilities<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. This means that customers can connect their smartphones with the ACE One<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. Customers can use the pre-installed ACE Connect app on their phones in order to track their loan repayments and contact ACE customer services directly<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. ACE are using the ACE One's smart functionality to implement a flexible 'pay-as-you-save' model as the unit can now be remotely switched off if the customer stops paying for it<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>.\n\nThe Colorado State University has certified the ACE One as an IWA-ISO Tier 3 for emissions and efficiency, and 4 for safety in laboratory tests.<ref name=\"UltraCleanSafe\" /><ref name=\"ACE1GACC\">{{cite web |url=http://catalog.cleancookstoves.org/stoves/268 |title=ACE 1 Clean Cooking Catalog |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->  |website=Global Alliance for Clean Cookstoves |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\nThe product has been field tested in Cambodia by the Berkeley Air Monitoring Group, who estimate that every 25,000 units in use will avert as many as 40 early deaths, and avert 1,295 [[Disability-adjusted life years]] (aDALYs).<ref name=\"SNVBerkeley\">{{cite report |last=Delapena |first=Samantha |last2=Garland |first2=Charity |last3=Jagoe |first3=Kirstie |last4=Okada |first4=Emi |last5=Ouk |first5=Sambath |last6=Pennise |first6=David |last7=Pillarisetti |first7=Ajay |last8=Steele |first8=Jason |title=Quantifying the health impacts of ACE-1 biomass and biogas stoves in Cambodia Final Report December 2015 Prepared by Berkeley Air Monitoring Group Commissioned by SNV Netherlands Development Organisation |date=December 2015 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/26/young-entrepreneur-judith-walker-ace_n_5875412.html |publisher=SNV Netherlands Development Organisation |pages=25, 41 |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Key Features===\n\n* Fuel Savings: Through efficient [[combustion]], the ACE One can reduce fuel use by up to 70% compared to an open fire. In Cambodia, researchers found that the product reduces fuel use by 52% compared to traditional Khmer stoves.<ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" /><ref name=\"SNVBerkeley\" /><ref name=\"5AfricanStartups\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lyndseygilpin/2015/08/17/5-african-cleantech-startups-you-need-to-watch/#7c238f7b32f5 |title=5 African Cleantech Startups You Need To Watch |last=Gilpin |first=Lyndsey |date=17 August 2015 |website=Forbes |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> By using the ACE One, customers can cut their basic energy expenses by up to 80%<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. \n* Reduced Emissions: The ACE One burns [[biomass fuels]] without smoke, reducing CO and PM 2.5 emissions by as much as 95% compared to an open fire.<ref name=\"UltraCleanSafe\" /><ref name=\"WaysSaveMarieClaire\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=6 Simple Ways To Save The World |url=http://www.africancleanenergy.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Marie-Claire-spread.pdf |magazine=Marie Claire |location=US |date= November 2014 |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n* Solar Electricity: The ACE One has an integrated USB port which can be used for charging mobile devices. The product also includes an LED lamp attachment.<ref name=\"DutchSocialEntrepreneur\" /><ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" />\n\n==The Business Model==\nAfrican Clean Energy is a for-profit company.<ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" />\nIt is currently active in Lesotho, Cambodia and Uganda, and its flagship factory is located in Lesotho.<ref name=\"AMSMagazine2017\" />\nThe ACE One is sold direct to consumers in these countries using an instalment-based payment model at a cost of about $100 each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> This ensures that the product is affordable to people who would be unable to afford a large lump sum payment.<ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" />To date, the company has sold about 60,000 units. The company has a potential market of approximately 900 million households.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> ACE is currently expanding its mobile retail shops to give more people access to its products and services, in a project which is being co-funded by the [[European Union|European Union.]] \nAfrican Clean Energy sponsors ACE Maseru FC, an A division football team in Lesotho.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> The company also manages the Lesotho Orphans Project, an initiative for donating stoves to orphaned children in Lesotho. ACE is an equal opportunity employer, that has committed to ensuring that 50% of employees are women.<ref name=\"DutchSocialEntrepreneur\" />The company currently employs 193 people globally and another 12 in Amsterdam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investforgood.blog/blog/clearing-the-air|title=Clearing the Air \u2022 Invest for Good|website=www.investforgood.blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Social enterprises]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Amsterdam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=December 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = African Clean Energy\n| logo = [[File:ACE Logo Small.png|ACE Logo Small.png]]\n| location = [[Amsterdam]]\n}}\n'''African Clean Energy''' is a [[social enterprise]] that produces and distributes solar-biomass hybrid energy systems in [[developing countries]]. The company was founded in Lesotho, where it manufactures the ACE 1 Ultra Clean Biomass Cookstove. The company's headquarters are in Amsterdam, The Netherlands.<ref name=\"DutchSocialEntrepreneur\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/devinthorpe/2015/09/02/dutch-social-entrepreneur-works-to-save-lives-in-africa-with-high-tech-stove/2/#13780e96f914 |title=Dutch Social Entrepreneur Works To Save Lives In Africa With High Tech Stove |last=Thorpe |first=Devin |date=2 September 2015 |website=Forbes |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\">{{cite book |last=Haber |first=Jason |date=16 May 2016 |title=The Business of Good, Social Entrepreneurship and the New Bottom Line |url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=A5IfDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&pg=GBS.PT30.w.5.0.105 |publisher=Entrepreneur Press |pages=16\u201317 |isbn=9781613083369}}</ref><ref name=\"AMSMagazine2017\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Update:Social Enterprises |url=https://s3-eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/africancleanenergy-storage-temp/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Amsteram-Magazine-Talent-Issue.png |magazine=AMS Business Magazine |location=Amsterdam |date=2017 |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nAfrican Clean Energy is a family-owned business, established in 2011. The ACE 1 was developed in 2014 with support from crowdfunding and the [[Global Alliance for Clean Cookstoves]].<ref name=\"YoungJudithWalker\">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/26/young-entrepreneur-judith-walker-ace_n_5875412.html |title=Young Entrepreneur Of The Week: 24-Year-Old Judith Walker |last=Bennett |first=Asa |date=26 September 2014 |website=Huffpost |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\nAs of 2017, the company is active in Lesotho, Cambodia and Uganda.<ref name=\"AMSMagazine2017\" />\n\n==The Biomass Cooking Sector==\n\nMore than 3 billion people cook using solid [[biomass fuels]] like wood, crop waste, coal and animal dung. The World Health Organization estimates that 4.3 million people die prematurely every year from illnesses attributable to household air pollution from burning solid fuels. Exposure to indoor smoke is particularly high amongst women and girl children, who are typically responsible for cooking. There are also 1.2 billion people without access to electricity, who currently rely on dangerous fuels like kerosene for lighting.<ref name=\"HouseholdAir\">{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs292/en/ |title=Household air pollution and health |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=February 2016 |website=World Health Organization |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe ACE 1 Ultra Clean Biomass Cookstove was designed to address these issues, while still being compatible with widely available biomass fuels. It is capable of burning any type of solid biomass smokelessly, and provides electricity for households that do not have access to the grid.<ref name=\"UltraCleanSafe\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Ultra Clean and Super Safe |url=https://issuu.com/imarketinsights/docs/imarket_insights_issue_02_2017 |magazine=IMarket Insights |publisher=Sunil Bhat |pages=30, 32 |date= 2017 |access-date= 29 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==The Product==\n\n===Functionality===\n\nThe ACE 1 has an integrated lithium-ion ferrophosphate battery which powers a small fan. The fan draws oxygen into the burning chamber of the device, intensifying the fire inside. This causes the biomass to gasify, ensuring complete combustion and creating a smokeless flame. The battery will power the fan for 20 hours, and can be charged using the included 5W solar panel.<ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" /><ref name=\"GearWired\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Gear |url=http://www.africancleanenergy.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/WIRED-MAG.jpg |magazine=Wired Magazine |location= |publisher=Rupert Turnbull |page=69 |date= 2015 |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref> The Colorado State University has certified the ACE 1 as an IWA-ISO Tier 3 for emissions and efficiency, and 4 for safety in laboratory tests.<ref name=\"UltraCleanSafe\" /><ref name=\"ACE1GACC\">{{cite web |url=http://catalog.cleancookstoves.org/stoves/268 |title=ACE 1 Clean Cooking Catalog |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->  |website=Global Alliance for Clean Cookstoves |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\nThe product has been field tested in Cambodia by the Berkeley Air Monitoring Group, who estimate that every 25,000 units in use will avert as many as 40 early deaths, and avert 1,295 [[Disability-adjusted life years]] (aDALYs).<ref name=\"SNVBerkeley\">{{cite report |last=Delapena |first=Samantha |last2=Garland |first2=Charity |last3=Jagoe |first3=Kirstie |last4=Okada |first4=Emi |last5=Ouk |first5=Sambath |last6=Pennise |first6=David |last7=Pillarisetti |first7=Ajay |last8=Steele |first8=Jason |title=Quantifying the health impacts of ACE-1 biomass and biogas stoves in Cambodia Final Report December 2015 Prepared by Berkeley Air Monitoring Group Commissioned by SNV Netherlands Development Organisation |date=December 2015 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/26/young-entrepreneur-judith-walker-ace_n_5875412.html |publisher=SNV Netherlands Development Organisation |pages=25, 41 |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Key Features===\n\n* Fuel Savings: Through efficient [[combustion]], the ACE 1 can reduce fuel use by up to 70% compared to an open fire. In Cambodia, researchers found that the product reduces fuel use by 52% compared to traditional Khmer stoves.<ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" /><ref name=\"SNVBerkeley\" /><ref name=\"5AfricanStartups\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lyndseygilpin/2015/08/17/5-african-cleantech-startups-you-need-to-watch/#7c238f7b32f5 |title=5 African Cleantech Startups You Need To Watch |last=Gilpin |first=Lyndsey |date=17 August 2015 |website=Forbes |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n* Reduced Emissions: The ACE 1 burns [[biomass fuels]] without smoke, reducing CO and PM 2.5 emissions by as much as 95% compared to an open fire.<ref name=\"UltraCleanSafe\" /><ref name=\"WaysSaveMarieClaire\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=6 Simple Ways To Save The World |url=http://www.africancleanenergy.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Marie-Claire-spread.pdf |magazine=Marie Claire |location=US |date= November 2014 |access-date=29 December 2017}}</ref>\n* Solar Electricity: The ACE 1 has an integrated USB port which can be used for charging mobile devices. The product also includes an LED lamp attachment.<ref name=\"DutchSocialEntrepreneur\" /><ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" />\n\n==The Business Model==\nAfrican Clean Energy is a for-profit company.<ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" />\nIt is currently active in Lesotho, Cambodia and Uganda, and its flagship factory is located in Lesotho.<ref name=\"AMSMagazine2017\" />\nThe product is sold direct to consumers in these countries using an instalment-based payment model. This ensures that the product is affordable to people who would be unable to afford a large lump sum payment.<ref name=\"BusinessOfGood\" />\nThe company also manages the Lesotho Orphans Project, an initiative for donating stoves to orphaned children in Lesotho. ACE is an equal opportunity employer, that has committed to ensuring that 50% of employees are women.<ref name=\"DutchSocialEntrepreneur\" />\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Social enterprises]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Amsterdam]]\n", "name_user": "Maratudora", "label": "safe", "comment": "I used a new source to update information on the company, its history and business model.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_Clean_Energy"}
